				\begin{document}$$ P(A)=\left|T(A). Fn(A)\right| $$\end{document}PA=TA.FnAwhere T(A) is the moderated t-score of the gene A and the weight, Fn(A), is the function of the frequency of the gene A in the set of all pathways. The weight is defined such that reduced the contribution of the overlapping genes. The idea supporting this weighting is that whenever a differentially expressed gene appears in fewer pathways, it is assumed that particular gene reveals the evidence that those pathways are affected by the given condition. Therefore, the frequently appearing genes are assigned with a low weight close to the 0.0, while pathway-specific genes are assigned with a high weight close to the 1.0. Similar to what is done in Traca et al. method [16] the weight Fn(A) is defined as the normalized frequency of the gene A across all KEGG pathways in the scale of (0,1) as follows:6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
